Setting `@tracked` properties inside a task triggers normal Glimmer reactivity — the template re-renders as each property is updated. You can update multiple `@tracked` properties sequentially. For atomic updates (where you want all to update together), batch them using a single `@tracked` object assignment instead of multiple individual property sets.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component'
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency'

export default class PlayerCardComponent extends Component {
  loadPlayerCard = task(async (playerId) => {
    const response = await fetch(`/api/players/${playerId}`)
    const raw = await response.json()

    // Transform snake_case API response to camelCase + computed fields
    return {
      id: raw.player_id,
      name: raw.full_name,
      country: raw.country_code.toUpperCase(),
      battingAverage: parseFloat(raw.batting_avg).toFixed(2),
      strikeRate: parseFloat(raw.strike_rate).toFixed(1),
      highestScore: raw.highest_score,
      isActive: raw.career_status === 'active',
      displayLabel: `${raw.full_name} (${raw.country_code}) — Avg: ${raw.batting_avg}`
    }
  })

  <template>
    <button {{on 'click' (fn this.loadPlayerCard.perform @playerId)}}>
      Load Player
    </button>

    {{#if this.loadPlayerCard.last.value}}
      <div class="player-card p-4 border rounded">
        <h3 class="font-bold">{{this.loadPlayerCard.last.value.name}}</h3>
        <p>{{this.loadPlayerCard.last.value.country}}</p>
        <p>Avg: {{this.loadPlayerCard.last.value.battingAverage}}</p>
        <p>SR: {{this.loadPlayerCard.last.value.strikeRate}}</p>
      </div>
    {{/if}}
  </template>
}
```
Tasks can perform data transformation inline before returning. The transformed object becomes `task.last.value`. This pattern keeps component code clean by separating fetch logic from rendering, and the transformation is colocated with the fetch rather than scattered across computed properties.

